Natural history. In Taiwan , this forest dwelling bat is widely distributed, from low to higher elevations. It was found roosting in tree holes, but never in caves. Lactating females were found from June to August, depending on altitude. Males started showing enlarged testis in August. In Yenping (Fujian) three specimens (including the type ) were taken in holes of live bamboo stems in a mountain area at an altitude of about 1000 m (
Allen 1923
).
